Here's how to implement all three requirements:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage.xaml`

```xml
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

In your ViewModel (or code-behind), the command navigates back â€” but only after checking for unsaved changes:

```csharp
[RelayCommand]
async Task Cancel()
{
    if (HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard) return;   // user chose Stay â€” do nothing
    }
    await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");   // go back
}
```

### 2. Guard the hardware/gesture back button in `AppShell.xaml.cs`

The custom `BackButtonBehavior` only covers the **toolbar** back button. The Android hardware back button and swipe-back gesture fire through `OnNavigating`, so you need a guard there too:

```csharp
// AppShell.xaml.cs
protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
{
    base.OnNavigating(args);

    // Only intercept back-navigation (Pop)
    if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
        return;

    // Check if the current page is EditProductPage
    if (Shell.Current.CurrentPage is EditProductPage page
        && page.BindingContext is EditProductViewModel vm
        && vm.HasUnsavedChanges)
    {
        // Must get deferral BEFORE any await
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose Stay â€” block navigation

        deferral.Complete();  // always call this
    }
}
```

### Key points

- **`GetDeferral()`** â€” call it *before* any `await`; call `deferral.Complete()` in all code paths. Without it, async guards race against the navigation completing.
- **`BackButtonBehavior.Command`** â€” replaces the default toolbar back-button behavior entirely; Shell won't auto-navigate back, so your command must call `GoToAsync("..")` explicitly.
- **Two guard sites** â€” the `BackButtonBehavior.Command` handles the toolbar button; `OnNavigating` handles the hardware/swipe back. The dialog may appear from either path but not both, because the custom command bypasses `OnNavigating` when it decides not to navigate.
